---
import PageLayout from "../layouts/PageLayout.astro";
import PhotoLightbox from "../components/react/PhotoLightbox";

const personJsonLd = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Person",
  name: "Kyle Daley",
  url: "https://daleykd.com",
  image: "https://daleykd.com/daleykd.jpg",
  jobTitle: "Cloud Architect",
  description:
    "Software engineer and cloud architect with about twenty years of professional experience.",
  sameAs: ["https://github.com/DaleyKD", "https://linkedin.com/in/daleykd"],
};
---

<PageLayout
  title="About"
  description="About Kyle Daley — software engineer, cloud architect, Christian, husband, and father of three."
  jsonLd={personJsonLd}
>
  <!-- Photo + name block -->
  <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row items-start gap-8 mb-12">
    <PhotoLightbox
      src="/daleykd.jpg"
      alt="Kyle Daley"
      imgClass="w-full h-full object-cover rounded-full"
      wrapperClass="w-28 h-28 rounded-full shrink-0 ring-2 ring-neutral-200 dark:ring-neutral-700 overflow-hidden"
      client:load
    />
    <div class="pt-1">
      <h1
        class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-neutral-900 dark:text-neutral-100 mb-1"
      >
        Kyle Daley
      </h1>
      <p class="text-neutral-500 dark:text-neutral-400">
        Software Engineer · Cloud Architect
      </p>
      <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mt-3">
        <a
          href="https://github.com/DaleyKD"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-sm font-medium text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-300 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-brand-700 dark:hover:text-brand-200 transition-colors"
        >
          GitHub
        </a>
        <a
          href="https://linkedin.com/in/daleykd"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-sm font-medium text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-300 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-brand-700 dark:hover:text-brand-200 transition-colors"
        >
          LinkedIn
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Bio -->
  <div
    class="prose prose-neutral dark:prose-invert max-w-none prose-a:text-brand-600 dark:prose-a:text-brand-300"
  >
    <h2>Hi, I'm Kyle.</h2>

    <p>
      Christian first, then husband and father to three kids, and somewhere
      after that I'm a software engineer. That order is intentional. I enjoy
      what I do for a living, but it isn't who I am.
    </p>

    <p>
      I've been writing software professionally for about twenty years. Most of
      that time has been spent building enterprise applications, designing cloud
      systems, and working somewhere between software engineering and
      architecture. I've worked on everything from aging legacy applications to
      brand new SaaS platforms, and I've genuinely enjoyed both for different
      reasons.
    </p>

    <p>
      The older I get, the more I appreciate simple software. Not because simple
      is easy, but because simple usually means someone understood the problem
      well enough to stop being clever. I've written clever code. I've also been
      the guy maintaining that clever code five years later. Those are two very
      different experiences.
    </p>

    <p>
      I've made plenty of mistakes along the way. I've learned more from those
      than from most of my successes. Technology changes quickly. Skills get
      rusty. Every so often I find myself relearning something I was convinced
      I'd never forget. I've stopped seeing that as failure. It's just part of
      the job.
    </p>

    <p>
      One of the most rewarding parts of my career has been helping other
      engineers grow. I enjoy working with developers of every experience level.
      Sometimes that means answering a question, sometimes it's pairing on a
      difficult problem, and sometimes it's just giving someone the confidence
      to tackle something they didn't think they could. Watching people grow
      into roles they once thought were out of reach never gets old.
    </p>

    <p>
      You'll mostly find thoughts here on software engineering, cloud
      architecture, distributed systems, leadership, interviewing, and
      AI-assisted development. You'll also find quite a bit about my faith and
      my walk with Christ. I don't see those as separate parts of my life. My
      faith shapes how I approach my work, my family, and the way I try to
      treat people. It would feel strange to write about one without
      occasionally writing about the other.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- Outside the keyboard -->
  <div
    class="mt-12 prose prose-neutral dark:prose-invert max-w-none prose-a:text-brand-600 dark:prose-a:text-brand-300"
  >
    <h2>Outside the keyboard</h2>

    <p>I have entirely too many hobbies.</p>

    <p>
      One of them is designing guitar effects pedal PCBs through <a
        href="https://www.delykpcb.com"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer">delyk PCBs</a
      >. If you've ever wondered where the name came from, it's simply "Kyle D"
      spelled backwards. I thought it was pretty witty when I came up with it,
      and after all these years I suppose I'm committed to the bit.
    </p>

    <p>
      That hobby is on hiatus these days, but it's the kind of thing that never
      really leaves you. There's something deeply satisfying about designing a
      circuit, soldering it together, plugging it into an amp, and hearing it
      come to life.
    </p>

    <p>
      I also enjoy taking things apart just to see how they work. Sometimes I
      even manage to put them back together again. Whether it's electronics,
      software, cloud infrastructure, or some random project around the house,
      I'm happiest when I'm learning how something works and figuring out how it
      could work a little better.
    </p>

    <p>
      My heart brightens when I hear my kids sing hymns at the top of their
      lungs. My soul rejoices when I teach the Trailmen in our Trail Life troop
      a new song, then hear them and their dads sing it loudly and courageously.
      I love stretching my mind by going a little deeper into theology and
      learning about apologetics. My body aches as I try to learn the basics of
      taekwondo.
    </p>

    <p>
      If any of that sounds interesting, welcome. I hope you find something
      here that's useful—or at least something that makes you think.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageLayout>
